![high](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/high-priority.svg)

If a thread is harvested again, it means it is currently unresolved on GitHub. If it was previously marked as `"done"` or `"wontfix"` in our ledger, keeping that status means the ledger will permanently consider it resolved, and `/act debt` will never select it for fixing again. Reopened threads must have their status reset to `"open"` so they can be queued for review debt resolution.

```suggestion
    if (prev.status === "done" || prev.status === "wontfix") {
      byId.set(row.thread_id, {
        ...row,
        times_seen: prev.times_seen + 1,
        status: "open",
        notes: prev.notes ? "Reopened. Previous notes: " + prev.notes : "Reopened",
      });
      continue;
    }
```

![medium](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/medium-priority.svg)

If `gh pr view` fails for any single PR (e.g., due to a transient network issue, rate limiting, or an invalid/deleted PR ID), the entire batch process will crash. Wrapping the `gh` call and JSON parsing inside the loop in a `try-catch` block will make the batch harvest much more robust by allowing it to log a warning and continue processing the remaining PRs.

```typescript
  for (const number of opts.prIds) {
    try {
      const viewed = JSON.parse(
        gh([
          "pr",
          "view",
          String(number),
          "--repo",
          `${opts.owner}/${opts.repo}`,
          "--json",
          "number,mergedAt,author,labels,state",
        ]),
      ) as {
        number: number;
        mergedAt: string | null;
        state: string;
        author?: { login?: string };
        labels?: Array<{ name: string }>;
      };
      if (viewed.state !== "MERGED" || !viewed.mergedAt) {
        console.error(`warning: PR #${number} is not merged — skipped`);
        continue;
      }
      out.push({
        number: viewed.number,
        mergedAt: viewed.mergedAt,
        author: viewed.author?.login ?? "unknown",
        labels: (viewed.labels ?? []).map((l) => l.name),
      });
    } catch (err) {
      console.error(`warning: failed to fetch PR #${number} — ${err instanceof Error ? err.message : err}`);
    }
  }
```

![medium](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/medium-priority.svg)

When a thread is moved back to `"open"` or `"claimed"` (reopened), keeping the old `fixed_at` timestamp and `fix_pr` number is misleading because the thread is currently active and unresolved. These fields should be reset to `null` when the status is not closed.

```typescript
    const isClosed = args.status === "done" || args.status === "wontfix";
    return {
      ...row,
      status: args.status,
      fix_pr: isClosed ? (args.fixPr ?? row.fix_pr) : null,
      fixed_at: isClosed ? now : null,
      notes: args.notes ?? row.notes,
    };
```

![medium](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/medium-priority.svg)

If the parent directory of `args.outPath` does not exist, `writeFileSync` will throw an error and crash the process. Ensuring the directory exists by calling `mkdirSync` with `recursive: true` makes the command much more robust.

```suggestion
  if (args.outPath) {
    require("node:fs").mkdirSync(require("node:path").dirname(args.outPath), { recursive: true });
    writeFileSync(args.outPath, plan, "utf8");
    console.error(`wrote ${rows.length} item(s) to ${args.outPath}`);
    return;
  }
```
